   "source": [
    "# Fermi Surface\n",
    "\n",
    "Here code examples for Fermi surfaces are given. Fermi surfaces are band structures in 3D, i.e. distributions of $E(k)$ in the first Brillouin zone (1BZ). Therefore methods are similar to band structures, i.e. projections of $E(k)$ along the high symmetry lines of 1BZ. For band structures, please refer to the [Electronic Structure examples](https://crystal-code-tools.github.io/CRYSTALpytools/examples/electronic_structure/electronic_structure.html).\n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE**\n",
    "\n",
    "For 3D and 2D systems only.\n",
    "\n",
    "## The 'read_Fermi_surface()' method\n",
    "\n",
    "This method is defined in the `crystal_io.Properties_output` class. The fort.35 file generated by the 'DLV_BAND' keyword, which specifies the min and max band numbers and the size of k mesh.\n",
    "\n",
    "The screen output ('out' or 'outp') is strongly suggested to get Fermi energy. Otherwise the data in fort.35 is used, rather than the energy aligned to $E_{F}=0$.\n",
    "\n",
    "$E(k)$ is saved by a grid defined in reciprocal unit cell, rather than the grid defined in 1BZ."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "b175807a-7294-4051-b482-2a20f4b597b8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "NaCl Fermi energy = -6.59 eV\n",
      "NaCl grid size = Z 24 Y 24 X 24\n",
      "NaCl nband = 30\n",
      "NaCl spin = 1\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from CRYSTALpytools.crystal_io import Properties_output\n",
    "\n",
    "fsurf = Properties_output('fsurf_NaCl.out').read_Fermi_surface('fsurf_NaCl.f35')\n",
    "\n",
    "print('NaCl Fermi energy = {:.2f} {}'.format(fsurf.efermi, fsurf.unit))\n",
    "print('NaCl grid size = Z {:d} Y {:d} X {:d}'.format(fsurf.bands.shape[1],\n",
    "                                                     fsurf.bands.shape[2],\n",
    "                                                     fsurf.bands.shape[3]))\n",
    "print('NaCl nband = {:d}'.format(fsurf.bands.shape[0]))\n",
    "print('NaCl spin = {:d}'.format(fsurf.bands.shape[-1]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f3e2bd41-b343-4836-95f2-3f3c9f534ee7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For spin-polarized cases, the last dimension is doubled."
   ]
  },

      "MV graphene spin = 2\n"
     ]
    }
   ],

    "from CRYSTALpytools.crystal_io import Properties_output\n",

    "f2D = Properties_output('fsurf_GMV.out').read_Fermi_surface('fsurf_GMV.f35')\n",

    "print('MV graphene Fermi energy = {:.2f} {}'.format(f2D.efermi, f2D.unit))\n",

    "                                                            f2D.bands.shape[3]))\n",
    "print('MV graphene nband = {:d}'.format(f2D.bands.shape[0]))\n",
    "print('MV graphene spin = {:d}'.format(f2D.bands.shape[-1]))"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "78d75679-46d7-4e21-b990-66358ff6def8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The 'electronics.FermiSurface' class\n",
    "\n",
    "This class includes object-oriented methods for data analysis and quick plotting.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The 'get_bandgap()' method and 'bandgap' attribute\n",
    "\n",
    "Similar to `electronics.ElectronBand` class, this attribute gets VBM, CBM and band gap from $E_{k}$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "49ce0934-8e2e-47b3-ae9e-fee66ac3d0fe",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "NaCl band gap = 11.70 eV\n",
      "VBM position: X 1.0699 Y 1.0699 Z 1.0699\n",
      "CBM position: X -0.0465 Y 0.5117 Z 1.0699\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from CRYSTALpytools.electronics import FermiSurface\n",
    "\n",
    "fsurf = FermiSurface.from_file('fsurf_NaCl.f35', 'fsurf_NaCl.out')\n",
    "print('NaCl band gap = {:.2f} {}'.format(fsurf.bandgap, fsurf.unit))\n",
    "\n",
    "_, _, _, pos = fsurf.get_bandgap()\n",
    "print('VBM position: X {:.4f} Y {:.4f} Z {:.4f}'.format(pos[0, 0], pos[0, 1], pos[0, 2]))\n",
    "print('CBM position: X {:.4f} Y {:.4f} Z {:.4f}'.format(pos[1, 0], pos[1, 1], pos[1, 2]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4fdfd068-7bdb-45c6-8708-94862c75cb5f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For spin-polarized cases, this method returns to VBM/CBM of $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ states separately."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "2debe14c-6d3a-4504-a495-8e473043af96",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "MV graphene alpha band gap = 1.80 eV\n",
      "Alpha VBM = -0.0340 eV\n",
      "Beta CBM = 0.3848 eV\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from CRYSTALpytools.electronics import FermiSurface\n",
    "\n",
    "f2D = FermiSurface.from_file('fsurf_GMV.f35', 'fsurf_GMV.out')\n",
    "print('MV graphene alpha band gap = {:.2f} {}'.format(f2D.bandgap[0], f2D.unit))\n",
    "\n",
    "_, vbm, cbm, _ = f2D.get_bandgap()\n",
    "print('Alpha VBM = {:.4f} {}'.format(vbm[0], f2D.unit))\n",
    "print('Beta CBM = {:.4f} {}'.format(cbm[1], f2D.unit))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3b01d5a1-c752-4022-836b-42470178b624",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The 'to_bxsf()' method\n",
    "\n",
    "This method writes data into the BXSF formatted file used by [XCrySDen's Fermi surface viewer](http://www.xcrysden.org/doc/fermi.html). Currently only 3D systems are supported by BXSF format.\n",
    "\n",
    "Use the `band_index` option (starting from 1) to specify the band to dump. For spin-polarized systems, attach 'a' or 'b' for $\\alpha$ or $\\beta$ states."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "a333d18e-2469-4440-9109-eb2f4397fb1c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from CRYSTALpytools.electronics import FermiSurface\n",
    "\n",
    "fsurf = FermiSurface.from_file('fsurf_NaCl.f35', 'fsurf_NaCl.out')\n",
    "fsurf.to_bxsf('fsurf_NaCl.bxsf', band_index=['vb', 'cb'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dd443ed5-395d-4a98-926b-66e5ee9508ca",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Visualize the valance band in XCrySDen. The isosurface of -0.5 eV below $E_{F}$ is plotted.\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"./fsurf_NaCl_BXSF.png\" width=\"640\">"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d96e076a-72bd-4ba3-a622-2d6f46b08f6e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "The `electronics.FermiSurface.plot()` method plots:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. For 3D systems, isosurfaces of $E(k)$, which is plotted as 3D isosurfaces.  \n",
    "2. For 2D systems, the distribution of $E(k)$, which is plotted as the 3D surface, with XY plane as 1BZ and Z axis as energy.\n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE**\n",
    "1. [MayaVi](https://docs.enthought.com/mayavi/mayavi/index.html) is required for plotting, which is not installed by default.  \n",
    "2. Currently it is the only visualization method of CRYSTALpytools. There is no similar methods available in the `plot` module.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3D systems\n",
    "\n",
    "It plots 1 or more isosurfaces of the same band structure. Though in principle the user can also specify multiple bands with `band_index` and the same `isovalue` entry is applied to all the bands, it is not recommended and rarely tested."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "ac051b90-67dd-4010-8ad0-b6ce55896820",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from CRYSTALpytools.electronics import FermiSurface\n",
    "\n",
    "fsurf = FermiSurface.from_file('fsurf_NaCl.f35', 'fsurf_NaCl.out')\n",
    "fsurf.plot('vb', isovalue=[-0.3, -0.5, -0.7], interp='slinear', interp_size=2,\n",
    "           BZ_linewidth=0.5, BZ_color=(0.5, 0.5, 0.5))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1a69ade6-53c8-48cc-80ca-dcbb214839d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "<img src=\"./fsurf_NaCl.png\" width=\"480\">"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "### 2D systems\n",
    "\n",
    "For 2D systems, it is possible to plot multiple bands at the same time. `isovalue` is ignored."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "110089e2-4898-4027-9ab4-1445baca4078",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from CRYSTALpytools.electronics import FermiSurface\n",
    "\n",
    "fsurf = FermiSurface.from_file('fsurf_GMV.f35', 'fsurf_GMV.out')\n",
    "fsurf.plot(['5a', '5b', '6a', '6b'], colormap='jet',\n",
    "            interp='slinear', interp_size=3, BZ_scale=1.5)"
